# Day 23 – Power Pivot (DAX)

## Overview
Today’s lesson focused on using **DAX (Data Analysis Expressions)** within Power Pivot to perform more advanced analysis inside the Excel data model.

The dataset used for the exercises contained job postings with information about salaries, required skills, and locations.

DAX allowed calculations to be defined directly within the **data model**, enabling more flexible analysis across related tables.

---

## DAX Aggregation

The first concept explored was **DAX aggregation**.

Aggregation functions summarize data across a dataset. In this exercise, we calculated the **average number of skills required per job posting**.

Instead of restructuring the dataset manually, a DAX measure was created to calculate this value directly from the model.

This demonstrated how measures can summarize complex datasets efficiently.

---

## DAX Filters

The next topic focused on **filters in DAX**.

Filters allow calculations to focus on specific subsets of data without modifying the underlying tables.

One example compared **salary levels between U.S. and non-U.S. job postings**.

By adding filter logic inside the DAX measure, the model could isolate salary data for specific regions and perform comparisons.

---

## DAX Advanced: Filters and Relationships

The lesson then moved into more advanced scenarios combining **filters with table relationships**.

Because the dataset contained multiple related tables (such as salary data and job skills), relationships allowed calculations to reference information across these tables.

Using this setup, we calculated **median salary by skill**.

This highlighted how relationships enable more detailed analysis when working with normalized datasets.

---

## DAX Math and Filters

The final exercise involved combining **mathematical operations with filtering logic**.

This was used to estimate **skill likelihood**, which examined how frequently certain skills appear across job postings in the dataset.

By combining math functions with filters, it became possible to identify patterns and probabilities within the dataset.

---

## Reflection

Today’s lesson showed how DAX expands the analytical capabilities of Excel when working with a data model.

Instead of relying only on cell-based formulas, calculations can be defined at the **model level**, making it easier to analyze relationships between multiple datasets.

This approach shifts Excel from simple spreadsheet analysis toward a more structured and scalable data modeling environment.
